[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 11.2. It shows one way you could translate the appointment-scheduling-bot pipeline into working Python using boto3 against Amazon Bedrock (LLM with function-calling), Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases (managed RAG over visit-type and provider content), Amazon Bedrock Guardrails, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, and Amazon EventBridge. The demo uses a `MockBedrockRuntime` standing in for LLM-driven intent classification and tool-arg generation, a `MockSchedulingSystem` standing in for the institutional scheduling system (FHIR Schedule, Slot, Appointment resources, or a vendor-specific scheduling API), a `MockKnowledgeBase` standing in for the visit-type catalog and provider-directory retrieval, a `MockTable` for each of the three DynamoDB tables (conversation-state, conversation-metadata, tool-call-ledger), a `MockEventBus` for EventBridge, a `MockBookingJournal` standing in for the S3 booking-event journal, and a `MockCloudWatch` for the metric emissions. It is not production-ready. There is no real Bedrock Agents action group configured, no real Knowledge Base ingestion, no real Guardrail configuration, no API Gateway plumbing, no WAF rule tuning, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, no KMS customer-managed keys, no VPC endpoints to the EHR, no Object-Lock-protected booking-event journal, no Connect contact-center handoff, and no Secrets Manager wiring for the scheduling-system credentials. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of a transactional conversational AI pipeline that respects the input-screening discipline, the identity-verification discipline, the visit-type-mapping discipline, the slot-hold transactional discipline, the booking-claim verification discipline, and the audit-everything discipline this recipe demands. It is not something you would point at a hospital website on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The code maps to the ten pseudocode steps from the main recipe: receive the message and bootstrap the session with greeting and disclosure plus input safety screening (Step 1), classify intent and route in-scope or hand off out-of-scope (Step 2), verify identity at the assurance level the intent and channel require (Step 3), search for slots after mapping the natural-language reason for visit to an institutional visit type (Step 4), refine or select a slot through conversation and place a short-term hold (Step 5), confirm the booking by converting the hold into a booked appointment with the institution's notification workflow (Step 6), handle reschedule and cancel intents through the same general pattern with the appropriate transactional contracts (Step 7), handle booking failures and partial-success cases without losing the patient's trust (Step 8), screen the output for scope drift and unsupported booking claims (Step 9), and close the conversation, archive the durable audit record, and feed the booking-event journal (Step 10). The synthetic patients, providers, slots, visit types, and confirmation IDs in the demo are fictional; nothing in this file should be interpreted as advice from any real institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In production you would also configure an Amazon Bedrock Agent (or a custom Lambda-based orchestrator) with action groups defining the scheduling tools (`patient_lookup`, `slot_search`, `slot_hold`, `slot_book`, `slot_reschedule`, `slot_cancel`, optionally `eligibility_check`), each backed by a tool-implementation Lambda that wraps the institution's scheduling-system API (FHIR scheduling endpoints from the EHR, a vendor-specific scheduling API, or an integration-engine layer). You would also configure an Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Base ingesting curated content from S3 covering the visit-type catalog (each visit type with its purpose, duration, scheduling rules, and prep instructions), the provider directory (specialty, languages spoken, accepting new patients, telehealth availability, established-patient rules), the location directory (address, parking, accessibility, insurance acceptance per provider), and the pre-visit prep instructions per visit type. You would configure an Amazon Bedrock Guardrail with restricted-topic filters for clinical-advice and account-specific-billing categories, an API Gateway endpoint fronting the chat-handler Lambda, an AWS WAF web ACL with stricter rate limits on the booking endpoint than on the FAQ endpoint, the three DynamoDB tables (conversation-state, conversation-metadata, tool-call-ledger), an Amazon S3 bucket with Object Lock in compliance mode for the booking-event journal, an EventBridge bus for booking-lifecycle events (`conversation_started`, `booking_proposed`, `booking_held`, `booking_confirmed`, `booking_failed`, `booking_compensated`, `conversation_closed`), a Kinesis Data Firehose delivery stream for the conversation-audit archive, AWS Secrets Manager secrets for the scheduling-system credentials, and (where applicable) the Connect contact-center integration for the live-scheduler handoff path. The demo replaces all of these with small mocks so the focus stays on the per-turn classification, identity-verification, visit-type-mapping, slot-hold-and-book, and disposition logic rather than on the platform plumbing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock:InvokeModel` for the intent-classifier model and for the orchestration model that decides tool calls and composes responses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock-agent-runtime:InvokeAgent` if you wire Bedrock Agents instead of running the orchestration in a custom Lambda
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock:Retrieve` and `bedrock:RetrieveAndGenerate` on the Knowledge Base ARN that holds the visit-type catalog and provider content
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock:ApplyGuardrail` on the Guardrail ARN you configured for restricted-topic and harmful-content filtering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, `dynamodb:Query` on the conversation-state, conversation-metadata, and tool-call-ledger tables, scoped to the specific table ARNs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `events:PutEvents` on the scheduling-events bus for emitting booking-lifecycle events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `firehose:PutRecord` on the audit-archive Firehose delivery stream
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:PutObject` on the booking-event-journal bucket prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for the operational metrics (booking completion rate, time to booking, identity-verification success, tool-call success per tool, slot-hold-but-not-confirmed rate, per-cohort slices)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `secretsmanager:GetSecretValue` on the scheduling-system credential secrets pinned to the current rotation version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the customer-managed keys protecting the conversation tables, the tool-call ledger, the booking-event journal, the audit archive, and the Secrets Manager secrets
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - For the tool Lambdas that call the institution's scheduling system: VPC-endpoint or PrivateLink permissions to reach the EHR's scheduling API, plus whatever the EHR's own auth flow requires
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each Lambda's IAM role to the specific resource ARNs it touches. The tutorial-level permissions above are fine for learning and will fail any serious IAM review. The chat-handler Lambda has Bedrock invocation and read-write on the conversation tables, but no direct access to the scheduling system. Each tool-implementation Lambda has scoped access to the scheduling system endpoint it calls plus write access to the tool-call ledger; the slot-book Lambda also has write access to the booking-event journal. Avoid wildcard actions and resources in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The visit-type catalog is the bot.** The code below assumes the visit-type catalog is curated, dated, and version-controlled. Cleaning it up is the project. Skip the cleanup and the bot books the wrong visit types; do the cleanup and the bot books the right ones. The `VISIT_TYPE_CATALOG` placeholder in the config is where you wire in your real taxonomy (in production this lives in a Bedrock Knowledge Base, not in code).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Tool calls are the bot's contract with the scheduling system.** Every action that affects the schedule goes through a tool with a well-defined contract: arguments schema, response schema, error codes, idempotency semantics. The LLM proposes; the tools execute. The demo collapses each tool into a Python function for readability; production has each tool as its own Lambda with its own IAM role and its own retry semantics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Slot hold is the safety net for concurrency.** Without slot hold, two patients can race to book the same slot through different channels and one of them ends up double-booked. The demo follows the search-then-hold-then-confirm-then-book flow strictly; production additionally instruments the slot-hold-but-not-confirmed rate as an operational metric and investigates elevated rates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Identity verification is graduated by intent and channel.** A patient logged into the patient portal asking to check their next appointment needs lower assurance than a patient on an unauthenticated web chat asking to cancel a same-day appointment. The demo's `IDENTITY_POLICY` table maps `(intent, authenticated, hours_to_appointment)` to a required assurance level. Production owns the policy as a versioned governance artifact reviewed by the privacy officer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The booking is durable; the conversation is not.** Once the appointment is booked, the source of truth is the scheduling system. The conversation log is the audit trail of how the booking happened, but the appointment itself lives in the EHR. The booking-event journal in S3 is the institution's durable record of every booking, reschedule, and cancellation the bot performed, separate from the EHR's own record, used for auditing and for compensation operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Conversation logs are PHI by association.** A patient interacting with the institution's scheduling bot has identified themselves as a patient of the institution. The conversation log is HIPAA-relevant. Audit logging, encryption, access controls, and retention policies apply. The demo writes a redacted record; production writes through Firehose into an Object-Lock S3 bucket sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, the state's medical-records-retention rules, and the institutional regulatory floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The output check verifies booking claims against tool results.** A bot that says "your appointment is confirmed" when the booking tool did not actually return success is a bot that lets patients show up for appointments that do not exist. The demo's `screen_output` extracts confirmation claims and verifies that each claim is supported by a successful `slot_book` tool result; production extends this with stronger LLM-based claim-vs-evidence checks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB rejects Python `float`.** Every confidence score, threshold, time-window, and numeric metadata field passes through `Decimal` on its way in and on its way out. The `_to_decimal` helper handles it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The example collapses many Lambdas into a single Python file.** In production the chat handler, the input-screening function, the identity-verification function, each tool-implementation function, the output-screening function, and the audit-archival function are separate Lambdas with their own IAM roles, error handling, retries, and DLQs. Comments call out where the boundaries should fall.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. Resource names, model IDs, the visit-type catalog, the identity-verification policy, the per-intent target assurance levels, the persona and refusal templates, and the validation thresholds are what you would change between environments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import re
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import uuid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from collections import defaultdict
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from typing import Optional
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Structured logging. In production, ship JSON-formatted records to
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # CloudWatch Logs Insights for cross-call investigation. Conversation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # logs are PHI by association: the user's question may name visit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # reasons, providers, or other clinical context. Log structural
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # metadata only (session_id, intent, tool name, tool latency,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # tool outcome, identity-verification path), never raw user
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # utterances, never raw generated responses, never tool arguments
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # that contain identifiers, never the patient name or DOB collected
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # during identity verification. The full transcripts and full tool
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # calls live in the audit pipeline (Firehose + Object-Lock S3) with
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # appropriate access controls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry handles throttling from Bedrock, DynamoDB,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # EventBridge, Firehose, CloudWatch, S3, and Secrets Manager. The
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # scheduling-bot response window is tight: the patient is staring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # at the chat widget waiting, and a retry storm that adds 5 seconds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # of latency is operationally worse than a fast failure with a
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # graceful degraded-mode message. Cap the retries and let the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # graceful-failure path handle the fall-back.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     retries={"max_attempts": 3, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Module-level clients. Reused across Lambda invocations in warm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # containers so each invocation does not pay the connection cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m REGION = "us-east-1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m bedrock_runtime       = boto3.client("bedrock-runtime",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m bedrock_agent_runtime = boto3.client("bedrock-agent-runtime",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m dynamodb              = boto3.resource("dynamodb",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m eventbridge_client    = boto3.client("events",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m firehose_client       = boto3.client("firehose",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m cloudwatch_client     = boto3.client("cloudwatch",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3_client             = boto3.client("s3",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m secrets_client        = boto3.client("secretsmanager",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Resource Names ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Fill these in with your actual resource names. The demo prints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # what it would write rather than failing if the resources do
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # not exist; see run_demo() at the bottom.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CONVERSATION_STATE_TABLE      = "scheduling-bot-conversation-state"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CONVERSATION_METADATA_TABLE   = "scheduling-bot-conversation-metadata"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TOOL_CALL_LEDGER_TABLE        = "scheduling-bot-tool-call-ledger"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SCHEDULING_EVENT_BUS_NAME     = "scheduling-bot-events-bus"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m AUDIT_ARCHIVE_FIREHOSE_NAME   = "scheduling-bot-audit-archive"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOOKING_EVENT_JOURNAL_BUCKET  = "scheduling-bot-booking-journal"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE          = "SchedulingBot"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Bedrock Knowledge Base ID for visit-type catalog and provider
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # content. The Knowledge Base owns chunking, embedding, and the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # vector store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m KNOWLEDGE_BASE_ID             = "KB_PLACEHOLDER_ID"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Bedrock Guardrail for restricted-topic filtering. Configure in
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the Bedrock console with restricted topics for clinical-advice
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # and account-specific-billing at minimum. Pin to a specific
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # version, not DRAFT, in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m GUARDRAIL_ID                  = "GUARDRAIL_PLACEHOLDER_ID"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m GUARDRAIL_VERSION             = "1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Deploy-time guardrail. Any blank resource name is a deploy-time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # bug, not a runtime surprise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m for _name, _value in [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CONVERSATION_STATE_TABLE",     CONVERSATION_STATE_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CONVERSATION_METADATA_TABLE",  CONVERSATION_METADATA_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("TOOL_CALL_LEDGER_TABLE",       TOOL_CALL_LEDGER_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("SCHEDULING_EVENT_BUS_NAME",    SCHEDULING_EVENT_BUS_NAME),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("AUDIT_ARCHIVE_FIREHOSE_NAME",  AUDIT_ARCHIVE_FIREHOSE_NAME),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("BOOKING_EVENT_JOURNAL_BUCKET", BOOKING_EVENT_JOURNAL_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE",         CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("KNOWLEDGE_BASE_ID",            KNOWLEDGE_BASE_ID),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("GUARDRAIL_ID",                 GUARDRAIL_ID),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("GUARDRAIL_VERSION",            GUARDRAIL_VERSION),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     assert _value, f"{_name} must be set before deploying."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Versioning ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Every conversation turn carries the model version, the prompt
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # version, the Knowledge Base version, the Guardrail version, the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # visit-type catalog version, and the scheduling-policy version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # active at the time of the turn. This is how a future audit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # reconstructs which calibration was active when a particular
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # booking happened.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m PROMPT_VERSION                = "scheduling-bot-prompt-v2.4"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m AGENT_VERSION                 = "scheduling-agent-v3.1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m VISIT_TYPE_CATALOG_VERSION    = "vt-catalog-2026-04-15"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SCHEDULING_POLICY_VERSION     = "policy-2026-03-01"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INSTITUTION_ID                = "riverside-clinic"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INSTITUTION_DISPLAY_NAME      = "Riverside Clinic"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Model IDs ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Two model roles. Intent classification and parameter extraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # are cheap per-turn tasks where a smaller model earns its keep.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The orchestration model decides which tool to call when, with
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # what arguments, given the patient's request and the recent
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # conversation history; that work benefits from a stronger model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # If your region requires cross-region inference, use the inference
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # profile ID (e.g., "us.anthropic.claude-3-5-haiku-20241022-v1:0").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # TODO: verify the exact model IDs available in your region and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # account; Bedrock model availability evolves over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INTENT_CLASSIFIER_MODEL_ID    = "anthropic.claude-3-5-haiku-20241022-v1:0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ORCHESTRATION_MODEL_ID        = "anthropic.claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022-v2:0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Pipeline Tuning ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Below this confidence, we ask a clarifying question rather than
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # acting on the classification. Keep this on the conservative side;
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # better to ask than to misroute.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INTENT_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD   = Decimal("0.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Below this confidence on visit-type mapping, ask the patient to
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # clarify rather than booking the wrong visit type.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m VISIT_TYPE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = Decimal("0.7")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Slot-hold TTL. Long enough that a patient deliberating over options
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # has time to choose, short enough that abandoned holds release back
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # into the inventory quickly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m HOLD_TTL_SECONDS              = 300
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Intents ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SCHEDULING_INTENTS = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "new_appointment",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "reschedule_appointment",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "cancel_appointment",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "check_appointment",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "update_preferences",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m OUT_OF_SCOPE_INTENTS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "clinical_question":   "nurse_triage",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "refill_request":      "refill_bot",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "benefits_eligibility": "benefits_navigator",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "general_question":    "faq_bot",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "out_of_scope":        "live_agent",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Identity Verification Policy ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Maps (intent, authenticated_session, hours_to_appointment) to a
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # required assurance level. The privacy officer owns this policy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # in production; this Python dict is a placeholder for what is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # normally a versioned governance artifact stored in Parameter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Store or a dedicated policy service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Assurance levels:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #   "authenticated": patient logged in via portal; trust the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #                    session-bound patient_id directly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #   "basic":         name + DOB + one confirmation factor (last 4
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #                    of phone, ZIP code, or one-time code).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #   "step_up":       basic plus a one-time code to a verified
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #                    channel; used for higher-risk actions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m IDENTITY_POLICY = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Intent: list of (predicate_lambda, required_level) rules,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # evaluated in order; first matching rule wins.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "new_appointment": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: ctx.get("authenticated"), "authenticated"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: True, "basic"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "reschedule_appointment": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: ctx.get("authenticated"), "authenticated"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             ctx.get("hours_to_appointment", 999) < 24,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          "step_up"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: True, "basic"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "cancel_appointment": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: ctx.get("authenticated"), "authenticated"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             ctx.get("hours_to_appointment", 999) < 24,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          "step_up"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: True, "basic"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "check_appointment": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: ctx.get("authenticated"), "authenticated"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: True, "basic"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "update_preferences": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: ctx.get("authenticated"), "authenticated"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         (lambda ctx: True, "basic"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Confidence thresholds for the patient_lookup tool. The lookup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # returns a match score; below the threshold for the assurance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # level we either step up or hand off.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ASSURANCE_MATCH_THRESHOLDS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "authenticated": Decimal("0.0"),  # already authenticated
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "basic":         Decimal("0.85"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "step_up":       Decimal("0.95"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Visit-Type Catalog (illustrative) ---
